
<section>
  <title>Exercises</title>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Show that if <m>H</m> is a subgroup of index 2 in a group
        <m>G</m>, then <m>H</m> is normal in <m>G</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>(G:H)=2</m>, there are exactly two left
      cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>G</m>. One of these left cosets is
      <m>H</m>; since the left cosets of <m>H</m> partition <m>G</m>,
      the remaining coset must be <m>G-H</m>. So if <m>a\in G</m>,
      <m>aH=H</m> if <m>a\in H</m>, and <m>aH=G-H</m> if <m>a\notin H</m>.
      Similarly, we can show that <m>Ha=H</m> if <m>a\in H</m>, and
      <m>Ha=G-H</m> if <m>a\notin H</m>. Thus, <m>aH=Ha</m> for every
      <m>a\in G</m>, so <m>H</m> is normal in <m>G</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>H=\{A\in GL(n,\R)\,:\,\det A=\pm 1\}</m>. Prove that <m>H\unlhd GL(n,\R)</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Consider the function <m>\phi \,:\,GL(n, \R)\to \R^*</m> defined by
      <m>\phi(A)=|\det A|</m>. The map <m>\phi</m> is a
      homomorphism, since if <m>A,B\in GL(n,\R)</m>, then
      <me>
        \phi(AB)=|\det(AB)|=|\det A||\det B|=\phi(A)\phi(B).
      </me>
    </p>

    <p>
      Further,
      <md>
        <mrow>\Ker \phi\amp =\{A\in GL(n,\R)\,:\,
        \phi(A)=1\}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\{A\in GL(n,\R)\,:\, |\det A|=1\}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =\{A\in
        GL(n,\R)\,:\, \det A=\pm 1\}</mrow>
        <mrow>\amp =H.</mrow>
      </md>
    </p>

    <p>
      Since <m>H</m> is
      the kernel of a homomorphism from <m>GL(n,\R)</m> to another group, it must be a
      normal subgroup of <m>G</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>G=\Z_6\times \Z_{14}</m> and let <m>H=\langle 2\rangle \times \langle 4\rangle \leq G</m>. Since <m>G</m> is abelian, <m>H\unlhd G</m>. Find the order of the factor group <m>|G/H|</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Note that <m>|G|=6(14)=84</m>, and since <m>\langle 2\rangle =\{2,4,0\}</m> and <m>\langle 4\rangle =\{4,8,12,2,6,10,0\}</m>, <m>|H|=3(7)=21</m>. So <m>|G/H|=|G|/|H|=84/21=4</m>.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Consider the subgroup <m>\langle 18\rangle</m> of <m>\Z</m>.
      </p>
      <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Explain how you know that <m>\Z/\langle 18\rangle</m> is a group under left coset multiplication.
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          Find:
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              <m>|\Z/\langle 18\rangle |</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>|4+\langle 18\rangle |</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              <m>o(4+\langle 18\rangle )</m> in <m>\Z/\langle 18\rangle</m>.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Note that in <m>\Z</m>, <m>\langle 18\rangle =18\Z</m>, so we may denote <m>\langle 18\rangle</m> by <m>18\Z</m> throughout this problem.
    </p>
    <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        <m>\Z/18\Z</m> is a group since <m>18\Z</m> is a subgroup of <m>\Z</m>, and <m>\Z</m> is abelian, so every subgroup of <m>\Z</m> is normal in <m>\Z</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            <m>|\Z/18\Z|=(\Z:18\Z)=18</m>.
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <m>|4+18\Z|=\infty</m> (since <m>4+18\Z=\{\ldots, -14, 4, 22,\ldots\}</m>).
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            The subgroup generated by <m>4+18\Z</m> in <m>\Z/18\Z</m> is
            <me>
              \{4+18\Z, 8+18\Z, 12+18\Z, 16+18\Z, 20+18\Z, 24+18\Z, 28+18\Z, 32+18\Z, 18\Z\},
            </me>
            so <m>o(4+18\Z)=9</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>G=4\Z \times \M_2(\R)</m>, <m>H=\langle 2\rangle \times \langle I_2\rangle  \leq G</m>, and <m>K=\langle (23)\rangle \leq S_3</m>.
        Explain how you know that the set <m>G/H</m> is a group under left coset multiplication, while the set <m>S_3/K</m> is not.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>G</m> is abelian, <m>H</m> is normal in <m>G</m>, so <m>G/H</m> is a group under left coset multiplication. Since <m>K</m> isn't normal in <m>S_3</m> (for instance, <m>(12)K=\{(23),(13)\}</m> while <m>K(12)=\{(12),(13)\}</m>), <m>S_3/K</m> isn't a group under left coset multiplication.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>H=\langle r^2\rangle \leq D_4</m>.
      </p>
      <ol>
      <li>
        <p>
          Prove that <m>H\unlhd D_4</m>. (Hint: Refer back to <xref ref="dihedralgps">Section</xref>.)
        </p>
      </li>

      <li>
        <p>
          It follows that <m>D_4/H</m> is a group under left coset multiplication.
        </p>
        <ol>
          <li>
            <p>
              The distinct left cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>D_4</m> are <m>H</m>, <m>rH</m>, <m>fH</m>, and <m>frH</m>. Explicitly list the elements of each of these cosets of <m>H</m>.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Complete the group table for <m>D_4/H</m>, denoting each coset by <m>H</m>, <m>rH</m>, <m>fH</m>, or <m>frH</m>, as appropriate.
            </p>
          </li>

          <li>
            <p>
              Use the group table for <m>D_4/H</m> to identify a familiar group to which <m>D_4/H</m> is isomorphic.
            </p>
          </li>
        </ol>
      </li>
      </ol>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <ol>
    <li>
      <p>
        Note that <m>H=\{e,r^2\}</m>. By the last statement in <xref ref="diords">Theorem</xref>, <m>r^2</m> commutes with every element of <m>D_4</m>; moreover, <m>e</m> clearly commutes with every element of <m>D_4</m>. Hence, <m>H\subseteq Z(D_4)</m>, and so by <xref ref="znorm">Theorem</xref>, <m>H\unlhd D_4</m>.
      </p>
    </li>

    <li>
      <ol>
        <li>
          <p>
            The left cosets of <m>H</m> in <m>D_4</m> are
            <me>
              \begin{array}{rclcl}
              H\amp =\amp \{e,r^2\}\amp =\amp r^2H,\\
              rH\amp =\amp \{r,r^3\}\amp =\amp r^3H,\\
              fH\amp =\amp \{f, fr^2\}\amp =\amp fr^2H,\\
              \mbox{and \,} frH\amp =\amp \{fr,fr^3\}\amp =\amp fr^3H.
              \end{array}
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            <me>
              \begin{array}{r||r|r|r|r}
              \cdot \amp H\amp rH\amp fH\amp frH\\ \hline\hline H \amp H\amp rH\amp fH\amp frH\\ \hline
              rH\amp rH\amp H\amp frH\amp fH\\ \hline fH\amp fH\amp frH\amp H\amp rH\\ \hline frH\amp frH\amp fH\amp rH\amp H
              \end{array}
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>

        <li>
          <p>
            Since <m>|D_4/H|=4</m> and every element of <m>D_4/H</m> is its own inverse, <m>D_4/H\simeq Z_2^2</m>.
          </p>
        </li>
      </ol>
    </li>
    </ol>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>G</m> be an abelian group and let <m>N\unlhd G</m>. Prove that <m>G/N</m> is abelian.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Let <m>aN, bN\in G/N</m>. Then <m>(aN)(bN)=abN=baN=(bN)(aN)</m> (the first and last equalities follow from the definition of left coset multiplication, and the second equality holds because <m>G</m> is abelian). So <m>G/N</m> is abelian.
    </p>
  </solution>
  <exercise>
    <statement>
      <p>
        Let <m>N</m> be a normal subgroup of group <m>G</m>, with finite index <m>m</m>. Let <m>a\in G</m>. Prove that <m>a^m\in N</m>.
      </p>
    </statement>
  </exercise>
  <solution>
    <title>print=false</title>
    <p>
      Since <m>m=(G:N)</m>, <m>|G/N|=m</m>. The element
      <m>aN\in G/N</m> has an order, call it <m>d</m>, that must divide <m>|G/N|=m</m>.
      So <m>m=dk</m> for some <m>k\in \Z</m>. Then
      <m>(aN)^m=(aN)^{dk}=((aN)^d)^k=N^k=N</m>. Since <m>(aN)^m=a^mN</m>, we thus
      have <m>a^mN=N</m>, implying that <m>a^m\in N</m>, as desired.
    </p>
  </solution>
